@book{Krueger2012,
abstract = {Atrial fibrillation (AF) is the common cardiac arrhythmia. It can be managed pharmacologically and is more and more frequently cured using ablation therapy. The success rates of radio-frequency ablation however are not satisfactory, and the majority of persistent AF patients need to undergo multiple interventions. Computational modeling of the atria bears the potential of providing deeper insights into the cellular and tissue mechanisms causing AF.This thesis targets three fields of multi-scale atrial modeling. First, advanced models of the cellular atrial electrophysiology and regional fiber orientation are introduced. Second, novel methods to create patient-specific anatomical and excitation propagation models of the atria are described. Third, potential applications of personalized models in basic research and clinical practice are presented.The advances described enable the generation of reliable personalized atrial models from medical image and electrical data. The results mark an important step towards the patient-specific model-based AF diagnosis, understanding and treatment.},
